                            <comment id="15266" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Fri, 4 Nov 2005 23:23:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the suggestion! I&apos;ve refined SingleColumnRowMapper to automatically parse String into Number, if appropriate. The conversion still happens in SingleColumnRowMapper itself (through delegation to Spring&apos;s &quot;NumberUtils.parseNumber&quot; method), mainly to have full control over the conversion process (potentially being more tolerant than the JDBC driver would be).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15380" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Sat, 12 Nov 2005 06:58:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;After researching this a bit further, it seems that some databases have their own rules of how to convert into target types, even if just for specific cases. This applies, for example, to the Oracle RAW type and its conversion into a String, but it might potentially also apply to conversion into floats.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As a consequence, I have refined SingleColumnRowMapper to use the specific ResultSet.getXxx() methods as far as possible for well-known types, only resorting to ResultSet.getObject() and Spring-specific conversion for other types (and if no required type has been specified).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
